          "body": "Nehemiah 3 is one of the most socially comprehensive chapters in the Old Testament. The workforce includes the high priest (3:1), Levites (3:17), priests (3:22, 28), Persian-appointed district rulers (3:9, 12, 14-19), temple servants (3:26), and lay tradespeople: goldsmiths (3:8, 31-32), perfumers (3:8), and merchants (3:32). Shallum's daughters repair alongside their father (3:12). The men of Jericho, a city some eighteen miles away, build next to Eliashib (3:2). This diversity is not incidental — it is the chapter's implicit argument that the restoration of Jerusalem belongs to no single guild, tribe, or class. The goldsmiths who normally work precious metals repair city fortifications. The perfumers who compound temple incense carry timber and hang doors. The chapter refuses any category of service as beneath the mission. Vocational identity does not set the limits of kingdom work."
