          "body": "Embedded in thirty-two verses of near-identical formula are two deviations that carry all of the chapter's evaluative weight. The first is negative: 'the nobles of Tekoa did not support the work of their masters' (3:5). The Hebrew is emphatic — they did not bring their *necks* (*tsavvar*, their shoulders) to the work. Their social distance from manual labor calcified into moral refusal. The Spirit preserves their non-participation for all of Scripture, while the Tekoite commoners who did work are honored twice (vv. 5, 27). The second deviation is positive: Baruch son of Zabbai repaired 'zealously' (3:20) — the single adverb of quality in the chapter. Among forty-one named workers, Baruch alone is distinguished not by what he repaired but by how he repaired it. The chapter's theological economy is precise: God notices what others overlook — both the refusal and the zeal — and records them permanently."
