          "title": "Repairing opposite your own house — the motivational logic of personal stake",
          "body": "Seven times the chapter records that a worker repaired 'opposite his house' or 'beside his house' (3:10, 23, 28, 29, 30 — and variants in 3:16, 25, 26). The pattern is not coincidental but theologically transparent: when the wall section you fortify is the wall your family sleeps behind, your motivation is not abstract civic duty but immediate protective love. Nehemiah assigns sections by proximity — the man whose home is threatened by a breach repairs that breach. This is the chapter's wisdom about sustainable motivation: the community whose members have personal stakes in the sections they guard will guard those sections well. The principle is not selfishness but ordered love — those who love their own households are positioned to love the city, because their household's safety depends on the city's walls (cf. Nehemiah 4:14: 'fight for your brothers, your sons, your daughters, your wives, and your houses')."
